# Shibari Events Project Scope

- Build a static SPA hosted on GitHub Pages.
- Keep runtime fully client-side with no backend services.
- Follow a buyer's-guide style UX inspired by [MacRumors Buyer's Guide](https://buyersguide.macrumors.com/).
- Store event data in repository-managed, human-readable files.

# Architecture Constraints

- Use a frontend-only stack suitable for static hosting.
- Use TypeScript for application and automation code.
- Standardize local toolchain with `mise` (`node@lts`, `npm@latest`).
- Maintain one source of truth for event contracts: JSON Schema + derived TS types.
- Keep data files as source of truth and derive UI state from them.
- Do not hide business data in compiled artifacts.
- Avoid introducing infrastructure that requires secrets for normal operation.

# Product Behavior

- Show upcoming and active events, never past-only listings.
- If an event has no confirmed future date, compute and display an estimated next date from history.
- Persist only business statuses: `scheduled`, `on_sale`, `sold_out`, `waiting_list`, `tba`.
- Infer temporal states (`happening_now`, `upcoming`, `ended`) from dates during build/runtime.
- Always show direct links to website, FetLife, and mailing-list or contact channels when available.

# Deployment

- Keep the app deployable through GitHub Pages workflows.
- Keep generated site assets in the configured Pages output directory.
- Ensure daily rebuilds so date-derived states stay fresh even without manual edits.
